        notes: "HUD's Project-Based Rental Assistance (PBRA) program provides approximately 1.3 million safe, decent, and affordable housing units for low-income and very low-income households across the United States. As one of the federal government's la",
        source: "https://www.hud.gov/sites/dfiles/CFO/documents/2027_CJ_Program_PBRA.pdf",
        primaryBeneficiary: "Low-income renters",
        storyBlurb: "HUD's Project-Based Rental Assistance (PBRA) program provides approximately 1.3 million safe, decent, and affordable housing units for low-income and very low-income households across the United States. As one of the federal government's largest affordable housing programs, PBRA subsidizes the difference between market rents and what eligible low-income tenants can afford to pay, ensuring long-term affordability in privately owned multifamily housing.\n\nThe program works by attaching rental assistance to specific housing units rather than to individual tenants, creating a stable source of income for property owners who agree to maintain affordability standards and physical conditions. HUD's FY2027 Congressional Justification highlights the critical importance of contract renewals and funding continuity for the 1.3 million households who depend on PBRA for their housing stability.\n\nBudget pressures and appropriations uncertainty—including a reported lapse in appropriations in early 2026—pose ongoing risks to the program's ability to renew expiring contracts and maintain the existing stock of project-based assisted housing. Housing advocates have consistently warned that failure to renew PBRA contracts can lead to the loss of affordable units, displacement of vulnerable tenants, and conversion of properties to market-rate use, making sustained federal investment essential.",
