        primaryBeneficiary: "Low-income and unhoused Californians",
        storyBlurb: "California's Homekey+ program awarded $636.1 million in 2025 to create 37 affordable housing communities equipped with wrap-around supportive services. The program, funded in part by Proposition 1 passed by California voters, targets individuals experiencing or at risk of homelessness, including veterans and those with behavioral health challenges.\n\nHomekey+ represents an evolution of the original Homekey program, which rapidly converted hotels and motels into permanent housing during the COVID-19 pandemic. The expanded program broadens the model to include new construction and rehabilitation projects with integrated health and social services, recognizing that housing alone is insufficient for many residents who need ongoing support to maintain stability.\n\nThe $636.1 million investment is part of nearly $2.8 billion in total housing awards announced by HCD in 2025, marking one of the most significant years of affordable housing investment in state history. The program has drawn praise from housing advocates and local governments alike, though some critics have raised concerns about long-term operating costs and the need for sustained state funding commitments beyond initial capital awards.",
