        primaryBeneficiary: "Low-income families",
        storyBlurb: "Governor Gavin Newsom announced the transformation of six underutilized state-owned sites into at least 843 new affordable homes, deploying a strategy of converting surplus public land into housing as a key tool in California's affordability crisis response. The announcement, made in November 2025, emphasized the state's commitment to using every available public resource to produce new housing supply.\n\nThe six projects span multiple communities across California, targeting families who have been priced out of the state's increasingly expensive housing market. By using state land, the projects reduce one of the largest barriers to affordable development: high land acquisition costs. This approach also allows the state to impose long-term affordability covenants that preserve housing access for future generations.\n\nThe initiative is part of Governor Newsom's broader housing agenda, which also includes the Homekey+ program and nearly $2.8 billion in awards announced through the California Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD). Critics and advocates alike have noted that while these projects are welcome, California's housing shortage numbers in the hundreds of thousands of units, requiring sustained and accelerated production.",
