        storyBlurb: "Denver celebrated the groundbreaking of an affordable housing redevelopment at the historic Denver Dry Goods Building, a project that will rehabilitate 51 existing affordable units and convert underutilized commercial space into 55 new homes, for a combined total of 106 affordable residences. The project breathes new life into a historic downtown landmark while simultaneously addressing the city's pressing need for affordable housing.\n\nThe adaptive reuse of commercial space into residential units reflects a growing trend in Denver and other cities of repurposing underused retail and office space—particularly relevant in a post-pandemic environment where commercial vacancy rates have remained elevated. By targeting the historic Denver Dry Goods Building, the city is also engaging with historic preservation values, seeking to honor the building's architectural legacy while modernizing it for contemporary residential use.\n\nThe project is part of Denver's broader Expanding Housing Affordability framework and is backed by the Department of Housing Stability. Community stakeholders have generally supported the adaptive reuse approach, though some historic preservation advocates have called for careful attention to design standards to ensure that the conversion respects the building's significant heritage.",
