        primaryBeneficiary: "Mixed-income tenure",
        storyBlurb: "The Colorado Department of Local Affairs (DOLA) announced inaugural Transit Oriented Communities awards, directing funding to four communities to upgrade infrastructure that will support up to 720 units of affordable housing near transit corridors. The awards represent Colorado's first dedicated push to link affordable housing production directly to transit access, a strategy that aims to reduce household transportation costs while improving access to jobs and services.\n\nThe initiative recognizes that affordable housing sited near transit provides compounding benefits for low- and moderate-income residents: lower commuting costs, reduced car dependency, and better connections to economic opportunity. Denver and the surrounding region have struggled with affordability pressures as rapid growth has pushed housing prices well beyond the reach of working families, making transit-adjacent affordable housing a high-priority goal for state and local planners.\n\nThe four communities receiving awards will use the infrastructure funds to prepare sites and supporting systems—roads, utilities, and public amenities—that make affordable housing development financially feasible near transit nodes. Housing advocates have praised the program as an innovative alignment of transportation and housing policy, while some community groups have raised questions about displacement risks in neighborhoods targeted for transit-oriented densification.",
