        storyBlurb: "Florida enacted groundbreaking policy empowering local governments to approve affordable housing on properties owned by faith-based organizations, a significant expansion of sites eligible for affordable development. The policy, highlighted in the 2025-2026 Catalyst Training Schedule published by Florida Housing Finance Corporation, allows churches, synagogues, mosques, and other religious institutions to partner with affordable housing developers to utilize underused portions of their land.\n\nFaith-based land represents a substantial untapped resource for affordable housing in Florida, where religious institutions often own large parcels in established neighborhoods that are served by transit and community amenities. By enabling these sites for housing development while allowing congregations to retain their worship facilities, the policy creates a new pipeline of potential affordable housing without requiring the acquisition of expensive private land.\n\nFlorida Housing's Catalyst program has been providing training to local governments and developers on how to implement the new policy framework, reflecting the state's commitment to building capacity for affordable housing production at the local level. Housing advocates have praised the initiative as an innovative way to unlock new supply, though some have noted that actual project delivery will depend on individual congregations' willingness to partner with developers and navigate complex zoning and financing processes.",
