        primaryBeneficiary: "Mixed-income tenure",
        storyBlurb: "The Fort Lawton Army Reserve Center Redevelopment project proposes to convert a former military installation in Seattle into a mixed-use affordable housing community. The City of Seattle's Office of Housing has been advancing the project through a lengthy planning and environmental review process, including a cultural resources analysis to ensure that any redevelopment respects the site's historic and cultural significance.\n\nFort Lawton has been the subject of community debate for many years, with advocacy groups, particularly Native American tribes with historic ties to the land, raising concerns about the cultural and environmental sensitivity of the site. The cultural resources assessment reflects the city's commitment to conducting a thorough review before proceeding with development, acknowledging the layered history of the property.\n\nThe project has potential to deliver significant affordable housing in a city facing one of the most severe affordability crises on the West Coast. However, it remains in planning stages, with community input and environmental review processes still ongoing. The balancing of housing need, historic preservation, and indigenous cultural interests makes Fort Lawton one of Seattle's most complex and closely watched redevelopment proposals.",
