        primaryBeneficiary: "Low-income renters",
        storyBlurb: "The City of Seattle selected Mercy Housing, a nationally recognized affordable housing nonprofit, to redevelop the Lake City Community Center into a combined community center and affordable housing development. The project aims to address housing needs while creating vibrant shared community spaces in the Lake City neighborhood, representing a dual-purpose investment in both housing and community infrastructure.\n\nThe selection of Mercy Housing reflects the city's preference for experienced affordable housing operators with a track record of integrating supportive services and community programming. The combined approach—housing above or alongside a community center—maximizes the use of publicly owned land while preserving valued community assets that residents rely on for recreation, social services, and civic engagement.\n\nThe Lake City redevelopment aligns with Seattle Mayor Bruce Harrell's One Seattle Housing Agenda, which includes plans for approximately 900 units of affordable workforce and artist housing across the city. Community groups in Lake City have generally supported the concept of combined housing and community center redevelopment, though some residents have raised concerns about the loss of existing community center space during construction and the scale of new residential density proposed for the site.",
