        primaryBeneficiary: "Workforce and artists",
        storyBlurb: "Mayor Bruce Harrell's One Seattle Housing Agenda outlines a plan to develop approximately 900 units of affordable workforce and artist housing across Seattle, including live-work artist studios and family-sized units. The initiative recognizes that artists and working- and middle-class households have been particularly hard-hit by Seattle's housing affordability crisis, which has pushed many long-time residents and creative sector workers out of the city.\n\nThe inclusion of live-work artist studios is a deliberate effort to preserve Seattle's cultural ecosystem, which has been eroded as artists are priced out of neighborhoods they have historically animated. By dedicating units specifically to artists alongside workforce housing, the agenda seeks to maintain socioeconomic and cultural diversity in a city increasingly dominated by high-income tech sector employment.\n\nThe One Seattle Housing Agenda frames these investments within a broader comprehensive approach that also includes zoning reforms, increased density near transit, and partnerships with nonprofit developers. Community input processes are ongoing, with residents and neighborhood groups engaging on questions of where and how new density should be added, how artist housing will be allocated, and what protections will be provided for existing lower-income residents facing displacement pressures.",
